Q25. Give an example of a time you improved a process or performance in your project.
Situation: In the Medicare Member Portal, we were getting end-user complaints about slow load times on high-traffic portal pages — the member dashboard and enrollment status pages specifically.
Task: I needed to identify the root cause and fix it without disrupting live functionality.
Action: I started by profiling the EF Core queries using SQL Server execution plans and logging actual query times. What I found was classic N+1 — for every member record being loaded, we were firing separate queries to load related plan data and eligibility status. In high-traffic scenarios this was generating hundreds of database round trips per page load. I redesigned the query patterns — used Include() for eager loading where relationships were always needed, rewrote batch operations to use projection queries that fetched only the columns needed, and added AsNoTracking() on all read-only queries.
I also identified two stored procedures that were doing table scans instead of using indexes, rewrote them with proper indexing hints, and rebuilt the indexes.
Result: API response time dropped by 35%. Query execution time dropped by 40%. The user complaints stopped. My lead specifically acknowledged the improvement in our next sprint review. That work also became the baseline pattern for how we write EF Core queries across the entire portal going forward.

