The reason we chose monolith is practical. Our team is small, our deployment target is a single Azure App Service, and the domains within the portal — enrollment, eligibility, access control, audit logging — are tightly related. Splitting them into microservices would have added distributed system complexity — network calls between services, distributed transactions, eventual consistency — without giving us meaningful benefits at our scale.
That said, I understand microservices well — when they make sense, what problems they solve, and what complexity they introduce. The honest answer is that microservices are not automatically better. A well-structured monolith that's maintainable, performant, and deployable is better than a poorly designed microservices architecture any day.

Q36. Why did you choose Microservices architecture? What were the trade-offs?
In my current projects I haven't used microservices — we've used a well-structured monolith which was the right fit for our team size and deployment scale.
But I understand microservices deeply and can speak to when they make sense and what the trade-offs are.
You choose microservices when you have independent scaling requirements — for example, your claims processing service gets 10x traffic during open enrollment but your admin module doesn't. Or when you have large teams working on different parts of the system and you need deployment independence — team A deploys their service without waiting for team B.
The trade-offs are real though. You gain independent deployability and scalability, but you introduce network latency between services, distributed transaction complexity, the need for service discovery, and much harder debugging — because a single user request now touches multiple services and you need correlation IDs to trace it. You also need a mature DevOps pipeline — Kubernetes, container registries, health checks, circuit breakers — before microservices become manageable.
My view is — start with a well-structured monolith, identify the boundaries that actually need to be independent, and extract those into services when the pain is real. Don't go microservices-first because it sounds modern.

Q37. How did you manage error scenarios in your project?
We handled errors at multiple layers in the Medicare Member Portal — not just try-catch everywhere, but a structured approach.
At the global level, we have a custom exception handling middleware in ASP.NET Core. Every unhandled exception passes through this middleware, gets logged with full context — request path, user identity, timestamp, correlation ID — and returns a consistent error response to the client. The client never sees a raw stack trace.
At the service layer, we use custom exception types — for example, EligibilityVerificationException for third-party API failures, UnauthorizedAccessException for permission violations. This means the middleware can respond differently based on exception type — a validation error returns 400, an authorization error returns 403, an unexpected server error returns 500.
For third-party API calls — like the eligibility verification integration — we wrap calls in try-catch with specific handling for timeouts and bad responses. We log the full request and response for failed calls so we can diagnose integration issues quickly. I also added a monitoring alert in Application Insights for repeated third-party failures so we catch degraded integrations before users notice.
For database operations, we handle concurrency conflicts explicitly — especially important in a healthcare system where two agents might update the same member record simultaneously.
The overall principle is — fail gracefully, log everything you need to debug, and never expose internals to the client.

Q38. How did you handle authentication and authorization in your project?
In the Medicare Member Portal, authentication and authorization are central to everything — it's a healthcare application with strict compliance requirements.
For authentication, we use JWT-based authentication. When a user logs in, they receive a JWT token that contains their identity and role claims. Every subsequent API request carries this token in the Authorization header, and our middleware validates it on every request.
For authorization, we went beyond simple role-based authorization. I built a multi-tier access control system with four user types — admins, agents, members, and auditors — each with different permission levels not just at the feature level but at the data level. For example, an agent can only see members they manage — not other agents' members. This required custom authorization policies in ASP.NET Core that check both the token claims and database-level permissions.
I implemented this using ASP.NET Core's IAuthorizationHandler and policy-based authorization — so authorization logic is centralized and consistent, not scattered across controllers.
Every sensitive action also goes through audit logging — who accessed what, when, and what changed. This is enforced through a custom action filter so individual developers can't forget to log.
Since launch, zero compliance violations — which tells me the design is solid.

Q39. What was the deployment process followed in your project?
In the Medicare Member Portal, our deployment process is structured around TFS with a branching strategy that separates development, staging, and production work cleanly.
Developers work on feature branches. When a feature is ready, a pull request is raised and code review happens before anything merges to the main branch. We follow this consistently — nothing goes to main without review.
From main, we deploy to Azure App Service. We maintain separate App Service environments for development and production — so testing happens in a real cloud environment before anything touches production.
For local development, we use Docker — the entire development environment is containerized so every developer is running the same setup. This eliminated the "works on my machine" class of problems entirely.
Deployments to production are done deliberately — not automatically on every merge. We verify in the staging environment first, then promote. For database changes, we use EF Core migrations carefully — we review migration scripts before applying them in production to make sure there are no breaking changes.
The structured TFS branching workflow I maintained reduced deployment errors significantly across the team — which was one of the measurable outcomes of getting this process right.

Q40. How was code review done in your project? What standards were followed?
Code review is something I take seriously — both as a reviewer and as someone who mentors junior developers.
In our team, every pull request must be reviewed before merging. As a senior developer, I review PRs from junior team members regularly. My reviews are not just about finding bugs — I look at architecture, naming, performance implications, and maintainability.
When I review code, I comment with explanations. If someone wrote an EF Core query that will cause N+1 issues, I don't just say "fix this" — I explain what N+1 is, why this query causes it, and how to fix it. That way the developer learns, not just the code gets fixed.
The standards we follow — no business logic in controllers, service layer owns business rules, repositories handle data access only, async all the way for I/O operations, AsNoTracking for read-only queries, meaningful exception handling at every layer, and consistent logging using structured logging patterns.
I also introduced a practice of flagging performance-sensitive code paths in reviews — if a query is running in a loop or a method is being called in a high-traffic code path, we discuss it before it goes to production rather than after.

Q41. How did you handle database migrations in production without downtime?
This is something we handle carefully in the Medicare Portal because downtime in a healthcare application is not acceptable — members need to access their eligibility information reliably.
Our approach is to make migrations backward compatible. Before any migration goes to production, I review the generated migration script manually. The key rule is — never make a breaking change in a single deployment. For example, if we're renaming a column, we do it in phases: first add the new column and start writing to both, then migrate the data, then stop writing to the old column, then drop it in a later release. The application can run against both the old and new schema during the transition.
For additive changes — adding a new table or a nullable column — these are safe to deploy directly because the existing application code doesn't break.
For stored procedure changes, we version the procedure name or use a transaction wrapper so that if the deployment fails partway, we can roll back cleanly.
We also run migrations in the staging environment first and verify the application works correctly against the migrated schema before touching production. That validation step has caught issues before they ever reached live users.

Q42. How did you ensure code quality and code coverage in your project?
Code quality in our project is enforced through multiple layers — it's not just about automated tools, it's about culture.
At the process level, we have mandatory code reviews — nothing merges without review. I use reviews as a teaching opportunity with junior developers, which raises the overall quality of what gets written in the first place.
For coding standards, we follow SOLID principles consistently — single responsibility in our service classes, dependency injection everywhere, interfaces for all service dependencies so they're testable and swappable. I enforce this in reviews.
For testing, we write unit tests for service layer logic — testing business rules, permission checks, and data transformation logic in isolation using mocked dependencies. For integration-sensitive code like the eligibility verification integration, we have integration tests that verify the full flow.
Code coverage is something we track — we aim for meaningful coverage on business-critical paths, especially the access control and audit logging modules. Coverage for coverage's sake is not the goal — covering the paths that matter most if they break is.
We also use Visual Studio's built-in analysis tools to catch obvious issues — unused variables, potential null references, and async method patterns — before they reach review.

Q43. What CI/CD pipeline did you use? Explain the stages.
In the Medicare Portal we use Azure DevOps with TFS for source control and a pipeline that covers build, test, and deployment stages.
The pipeline stages are:
First — Build. When a PR is merged to main, the pipeline triggers automatically, restores NuGet packages, and compiles the solution. If the build fails, the pipeline stops and the team is notified.
Second — Test. Unit tests run automatically as part of the pipeline. If any test fails, deployment is blocked. This gives us confidence that merged code hasn't broken existing functionality.
Third — Deploy to Staging. After a successful build and test pass, the application is deployed to the Azure App Service staging environment. This is a real cloud environment — same configuration as production, same database structure.
Fourth — Manual approval for Production. We don't auto-deploy to production. A manual approval step is required — a senior developer or lead reviews the staging deployment, verifies it looks correct, and approves the production deployment.
Fifth — Deploy to Production. The approved build is deployed to the production Azure App Service slot.
The TFS branching strategy — feature branches, reviewed PRs, protected main branch — feeds cleanly into this pipeline and means what reaches production has always been reviewed, built, tested, and verified in staging first.

Q44. How did your team handle hotfixes or critical production issues?
We have a clear process for this because in a healthcare application, critical issues need fast, controlled responses — not panicked ad-hoc fixes.
When a production issue is identified, the first step is triage — understand the scope. Is it affecting all users or specific ones? Is data integrity at risk? Is it a display issue or a functional failure? This determines the urgency and response.
For genuine hotfixes, we branch directly from the production tag — not from main, because main might already have unreleased features. The fix is made on the hotfix branch, reviewed quickly but seriously — we don't skip review even under pressure — and then deployed to a quick staging verification before production.
A real example — when we had the eligibility status bug where members were showing as ineligible incorrectly, I identified the root cause within an hour using Application Insights logs, built the fix, got it reviewed, and deployed it within two hours of the issue being reported. After the fix, I also added a monitoring alert so the same class of issue would be caught automatically in future.
Post-incident, we do a brief retrospective — what caused it, what we missed in testing, and what process or monitoring change prevents it recurring. That last step is what turns a production incident into a learning that makes the system more resilient.




